'''William Allen "Bill" Stein''' (born January 21, 1947 in [[Battle Creek]], [[Michigan]]) is a retired [[professional baseball]] player and [[manager (baseball)|manager]]. His playing career spanned 17 seasons, 14 of which were spent in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) with the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] (1972<U+2013>73), the [[Chicago White Sox]] (1974<U+2013>76), the [[Seattle Mariners]] (1977<U+2013>1980), and the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] (1981<U+2013>85). Over his career in the majors Stein [[batting average|batted]] .267 with 122 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], 18 [[triple (baseball)|triples]], 44 [[home run]]s, and 311 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs) in 959 [[games played]]. Stein played numerous fielding [[baseball positions|positions]] over his major league career, including [[third base]], [[second base]], [[first base]], [[left field]], [[right field]], and [[shortstop]]. He also spent significant time as a [[pinch hitter]].

Stein was drafted out of [[Southern Illinois University]] during the [[1969 Major League Baseball Draft]] by the St. Louis Cardinals. He made his professional debut that season in their [[minor league baseball|minor league]] organization. On September 6, 1972, Stein made his MLB debut with the Cardinals. During the 1973 season, St. Louis traded him to the [[California Angels]], who just a few months later, traded him to the Chicago White Sox. Stein was selected by the Seattle Mariners from the White Sox in the [[1976 Major League Baseball expansion draft]]. He came to his final team, the Texas Rangers, by way of [[free agent|free agency]]. After his playing career, Stein managed in the [[New York Mets]] minor league organization for four seasons (1988<U+2013>1991). He managed the non-affiliated [[Bend Bucks]] in 1991, and joined the [[Clinton Giants]] in 1992, who were minor league affiliates of the [[San Francisco Giants]] at the time. He also managed the [[independent league baseball|independent league]] [[Tyler WildCatters]] in 1994.

==Early life==
Stein was born on January 21, 1947 in [[Battle Creek]], [[Michigan]]. Stein attended [[Brevard Community College]] when he was drafted by the [[Baltimore Orioles]] during the 33{{sup|rd}} round of the [[1968 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|title=33rd Round of the 1968 MLB June Amateur Draft|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/?query_type=year_round&year_ID=1968&draft_round=33&draft_type=junreg&|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref> Stein did not sign with the Orioles. He began attending [[Southern Illinois University]] in 1969.<ref>{{cite web|title=Southern Illinois University Salukis (Carbondale, IL)|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/schools/sillinois.shtml|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref> As a member of the school's baseball team, he [[batting average|batted]] .396 and was named an [[All-American]] by the [[American Baseball Coaches Association]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Canes, Florida State Place 2 On All-American|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VTwgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NmYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3529,3791691&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=15 June 1969}}</ref> Stein was drafted by the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] during the fourth round of the [[1969 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|title=4th Round of the 1969 MLB June Amateur Draft|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/?year_ID=1969&draft_round=4&draft_type=junreg&query_type=year_round|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref>

==Playing career==
===St. Louis Cardinals===
In 1969, Stein began his [[professional baseball]] career in the St. Louis Cardinals [[minor league baseball|minor league]] organization. The Cardinals assigned him to the [[Tulsa Oilers]], who were their [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] affiliates at the time. With the Oilers, Stein [[batting average|batted]] .295 with 24 [[runs scored]], 54 [[hit (baseball)|hits]], 11 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], five [[triple (baseball)|triples]], one [[home run]], and 20 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs) in 62 [[games played]]. Defensively, Stein played 31 games at [[second base]], 14 games at [[third base]], and five games at [[shortstop]].<ref name=brm>{{cite web|title=Bill Stein Minor League Statistics & History|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=stein-001wil|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref> During the 1970 season, the Cardinals assigned Stein to the [[Double-A (baseball)|Double-A]] level to play with the [[Arkansas Travelers]] of the [[Texas League]]. In 114 games played that year, he batted .289 with 124 hits, 21 doubles, two triples, and eight home runs. In the field, Stein played second base and [[outfield]].<ref name=brm/> In 1971, Stein was promoted to the Triple-A level. He spent the entire season with the Tulsa Oilers, where he batted .272 with 50 runs scored, 106 hits, 106 hits, 22 doubles, four triples, eight home runs, and 67 RBIs in 103 games played.<ref name=brm/> Stein [[pitcher|pitched]] a game that season, after Tulsa's starting pitcher was ejected from the game after throwing the ball at the [[umpire (baseball)|umpire]].<ref name="utility">{{cite web|title=Bill Stein has tried it all|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=0W4tAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wokFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2644,1834945&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Tri City Herald|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=7 March 1977}}</ref> In six [[innings pitched|innings]], he gave-up eight hits, and three runs (all [[earned runs|earned]]). He played the majority of the season in the outfield, but also spent limited time at third base, [[first base]], and shortstop.

To start the 1972 season, Stein was a member of the Triple-A Tulsa Oilers. With Tulsa that year, he batted .278 with 100 hits, 26 doubles, four triples, five home runs, and 36 RBIs in 103 games played. Stein was a [[September call-up]] for the St. Louis cardinals that year. He made his debut in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) on September 6, 1972, against the [[Philadelphia Phillies]].<ref name="72log">{{cite web|title=Bill Stein 1972 Batting Gamelogs|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=steinbi02&t=b&year=1972|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref> He got his first hit in that game, which was a home run in the ninth [[inning]].<ref name=72log /><ref>{{cite web|title=Night Games|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=1QwrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tJoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5240,4195514&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Reading Eagle|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=7 September 1972}}</ref> He played 14 games in the majors that year, batting .314 with two runs scored, 11 hits, one triple, two home runs, and three RBIs. Defensively in the majors, he was positioned at third base, left field, and [[right field]].

During [[spring training]] in 1973, the ''[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]'' labeled Stein as the Cardinals candidate for [[pinch hitter|pinch hitting]] off the bench.<ref>{{cite web|title=Murcer Inks Yankees Pact|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xnIjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rmYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5177,2190728&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|publisher=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=6 March 1973}}</ref> He made the Cardinals [[Opening Day]] roster that year. He made his season debut on April 6 as a pinch hitter, going hitless in one [[at-bat]] against the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].<ref name="73log">{{cite web|title=Bill Stein 1973 Batting Gamelogs|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=steinbi02&t=b&year=1973|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref> His first hit of the season came on April 17, against the Pirates.<ref name=73log /> In August, Stein was sent down to the minor leagues and was replaced on the Cardinals major league roster by outfielder [[H<U+00E9>ctor Cruz (baseball)|H<U+00E9>ctor Cruz]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cruz Elevated By Cardinals|work=The Victoria Advocate|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=10 August  1973}}</ref> In the minors, he played with the Triple-A Tulsa Oilers, where he batted .289 with 23 hits, two doubles, and one triple in 21 games played. While in the majors that season, Stein compiled a .218 batting average with four runs scored, 12 hits, two doubles, and two RBIs in 32 games played. On defense with the Cardinals, he played right field, left field, third base, and first base.

===Chicago White Sox===
On September 25, Stein was traded by the St. Louis Cardinals to the [[California Angels]] in exchange for [[Jerry DaVanon]].<ref name="trades">{{cite web|title=Bill Stein Trades and Transactions|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/trades.php?p=steinbi02|work=Baseball-Almanac.com|publisher=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref> California then traded Stein to the [[Chicago White Sox]] on April 3, 1974, before he made an appearance in the Angels organization.<ref name=trades /> In return, the White Sox sent [[Steve Blateric]] to California.<ref name=trades /> Stein started the 1974 season in the White Sox minor league system with the Triple-A [[Iowa Oaks]]. In 135 games with Iowa, he batted .326 with 107 runs scored, 178 hits, 32 doubles, eight triples, 16 home runs, and 76 RBIs. Stein led the [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]] in hits; was second in runs scored, [[plate appearances]] (594), at-bats (554), and doubles; and was tied for second in triples.<ref>{{cite web|title=1974 American Association Batting Leaders|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=10105&sort_by=PA|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref> He was called-up by Chicago in September.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chisox Gain Farm Pair|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-iArAAAAIBAJ&sjid=V4kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6023,2730104&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Schenectady Gazette|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=12 September 1974}}</ref> Stein made his season debut on September 13, against the California Angels, getting no hits in four at-bats.<ref name="74log">{{cite web|title=Bill Stein 1974 Batting Gamelogs|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=steinbi02&t=b&year=1974|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref> His first hit of the season came the day after, against California.<ref name=74log /> In the majors that year, Stein batted .276 with five runs scored, 12 hits, one double, and five RBIs in 13 games played.

Stein spent his first full season in the majors during the 1975 season. His season debut came on April 16, against the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], where in one at-bat he went hitless.<ref name="75log">{{cite web|title=Bill Stein 1975 Batting Gamelogs|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=steinbi02&t=b&year=1975|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref> In June, Stein was named the starting third baseman after [[Bill Melton]], who was Chicago's regular third baseman, was benched for poor hitting.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lassila|first=Alan|title=Changing Faces: Way of Life For White Sox|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_gwfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VI0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6686,1172639&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Sarasota Journal|publisher=Sarasota Journal|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=4 June 1975}}</ref> Stein also played back-up for second baseman [[Jorge Orta]] over the season.<ref>{{cite web|title=AL West: Angels shut out A's again|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/baltsun/access/1745815792.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jul+07,+1975&author=&pub=The+Sun+(1837-1985)&desc=AL+West&pqatl=google|work=The Baltimore Sun (subscription required)|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=7 July 1975}}</ref> On July 20, in the second game of a [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]] against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]], Stein hit his first career [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]].<ref name=75log /><ref>{{cite web|last=Lowitt|first=Bruce|title=Stein homers power Chisox past Brewers|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=IR4LAAAAIBAJ&sjid=WFADAAAAIBAJ&pg=4689,1206362&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=The Prescott Courier|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=21 July 1975}}</ref> On the season, Stein batted .270 with 23 runs scored, 61 hits, seven doubles, one triple, three home runs, and 21 RBIs in 76 games played. In the field, he played 28 games at second base, 24 games at second base, and one game in left field. Stein also played 18 games that year at the [[designated hitter]] spot in the [[Batting order (baseball)|lineup]].

Stein played his final season with the Chicago White Sox in 1976. On August 17, in the first game of a doubleheader against the [[Boston Red Sox]], he hit a game winning single in the ninth inning to score [[Pat Kelly (outfielder)|Pat Kelly]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Monty give Red Sox Tuesday night split|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zwE1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=Pk8KAAAAIBAJ&pg=3182,1426388&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Bangor Daily News|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=19 August  1976}}</ref> In August, [[United Press International]] noted that it was the first time in his major leaue career that Stein was getting a chance to start regularly.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rosenburg|first=Ken|title=A's gain on ailing Royals|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZBMQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZY8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3941,2487010&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=United Press International|publisher=Ellensburg Daily Record|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=14 August 1976}}</ref> During the season, he compiled a .268 batting average with 32 runs scored, 105 hits, 15 doubles, two triples, four home runs, and 36 RBIs in 117 games played. Stien played 58  games at second base, 58 games at third base, one game at first base, one game in right field, and one game at shortstop. He was also the designated hitter in one game during that season.

===Seattle Mariners===
{{quote box|width=24em|align=right|quote="The only thing [[Darrell Johnson]], the [[Seattle Mariners|Mariners]] [[manager (baseball)|manager]] told me is to work at [[third base]] [...] You get worn out if you just sit on the bench. I found it much easier to play everyday."|source= <U+2014>[[The Associated Press]] interviewing Stein in March 1977 on the subject of his new team, the Mariners.<ref name=utility />}}
During the [[1976 Major League Baseball expansion draft]], Stein was selected by the [[Seattle Mariners]], who took him with their third pick in the draft.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royals' Jones first choice in draft|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qVcyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KuYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4737,855884&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Lawrence Journal-World|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=5 November 1976}}</ref> Stein stated he was "glad" that the Mariners drafted him, because he did not like playing at [[Comiskey Park]], the home of his previous team, the Chicago White Sox.<ref name=june77AP /> He was profiled by the [[Associated Press]] during spring training in 1977, and was interviewed about his new team and his unique versatility in the field.<ref name=utility /> Stein mentioned to the reporter that although he had played a wide verity of positions in the past, he hoped he would get a chance to be the Mariners starting third baseman.<ref name=utility /> In a win against the Boston Red Sox on May 3, Stein hit two home runs in the same game.<ref name="77log">{{cite web|title=Bill Stein 1977 Batting Gamelogs|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=steinbi02&t=b&year=1977|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Stein, Mariners Outslug Red Sox|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GEYxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GOEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2705,797966&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=United Press International|publisher=Schenectady Gazette|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=4 May 1977}}</ref> In June, Stein commented on how he liked starting everyday at third base for the Mariners.<ref name="june77AP">{{cite web|title=Stein finally finds a home|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=M68pAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ml0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4723,2770713&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=St. Petersburg Times|accessdate=26 November 2010|date=4 June 1977}}</ref> The Mariners [[manager (baseball)|manager]], [[Darrell Johnson]], Praised Stein for playing "good ball" with Seattle.<ref name=june77AP /> On July 8, in a game against the [[Minnesota Twins]], Stein had another two-home run performance, his second of the season.<ref name=77log /> In early-September, Stein got hit in the [[shoulder]] by a baseball, which was later revealed to have caused a [[hairline fracture]].<ref>{{cite web|title=M's fade before Royals rally|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yok1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=rokFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2835,2057106&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Tri City Herald|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=8 September 1977}}</ref> With the Mariners that year, he batted .259 with 53 runs scored, 144 hits, 26 doubles, five triples, 13 home runs, and 67 RBIs in 151 games played. Defensively, the vast majority of his games (147) were played at third base, but he also played limited time at shortstop. He led the [[American League]] in [[putout]]s by a third baseman with 146.<ref name="77leaders">{{cite web|title=1977 American League Fielding Leaders|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1977-fielding-leaders.shtml|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=26 November 2010}}</ref> Stein was also fifth in the league in defensive games at third base.<ref name=77leaders />

Before the start of the 1978 season, Stein re-signed with the Seattle Mariners.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seaver remains bitter about Mets management|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=65BZAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3UkNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2742,125848&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=The Leader-Post|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=16 February 1978}}</ref> His contract meant he was now signed through the 1980 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mariners sign two players|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=unBUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bI8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=2248,2616055&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=United Press International|publisher=Ellensburg Daily Record|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=16 February 1978}}</ref> In May 1978, he bruised his left hand, which caused him to miss some playing time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mariner sub sinks Royals|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JqAfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=oNUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3579,3071633&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=The Southeast Missourian|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=21 May 1978}}</ref> On August 25, he broke-up [[Dennis Mart<U+00ED>nez|Dennis Mart<U+00ED>nez's]] potential [[no-hitter]] in the seventh inning of a game against the Baltimore Orioles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Orioles' Martinez Two-Hits Mariners|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=p4YsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zM0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5199,5299125&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Herald-Journal|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=26 August 1978}}</ref><ref name="78log">{{cite web|title=Bill Stein 1978 Batting Gamelogs|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=steinbi02&t=b&year=1978|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> On August 28, in a game against the Boston Red Sox, Stein had a season-high four hits.<ref name=78log /><ref>{{cite web|title=Error opens the door, Red Sox shut in, 10<U+2013>9|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BgdFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6uEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6791,8616237&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Eugene Register-Guard|publisher=Eugene Register-Guard|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=29 August  1978}}</ref> On the season, he batted .261 with 41 runs scored, 105 hits, 24 doubles, four triples, four home runs, and 37 RBIs in 114 games played. In the field, Stein played 67 games at third base, 17 games at second base, and three games at shortstop. His 24 [[error (baseball)|errors]] at third base was second in the American League.<ref>{{cite web|title=1978 American League Fielding Leaders|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1978-fielding-leaders.shtml|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref>

Early into the 1979 season, Stein was placed on the [[disabled list]] after suffering a [[rib]] injury.<ref name="79injury">{{cite web|title=Stein placed on disabled list|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hTEqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EIgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5165,9023540&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Tri City Herald|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=31 May 1979}}</ref> [[Charlie Beamon, Jr.]] was called-up from the minor leagues to replace Stein during his injury.<ref name=79injury /> In late June, the Mariners activated Stein from the disabled list.<ref name="activate">{{cite web|title=Stein celebrates return by sparking Mariner victory|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Dr40AAAAIBAJ&sjid=2YcFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1363,8583936&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Tri City Herald|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=28 June 1979}}</ref> By the time he had returned, the Mariners had already positioned [[Dan Meyer (first baseman)|Dan Meyer]] at his position, so Stein filled in at second base during his first game back.<ref name=activate /> That year, Stein batted .248 with 28 runs scored, 62 hits, nine doubles, two triples, seven home runs, and 27 RBIs in 88 games played. As a fielder, he played 67 games at third base, 17 games at second base, and three games at shortstop.

Stein's final season with the Seattle Mariners would come in 1980. On April 29, against the Minnesota Twins, Stein had a season high four hit game.<ref name="80log">{{cite web|title=Bill Stein 1980 Batting Gamelogs|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=steinbi02&t=b&year=1980|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> He matched that high on July 26, against the [[Toronto Blue Jays]].<ref name=80log /> On July 28, Stein broke up a no-hit bid by Cleveland Indians pitcher [[Len Barker]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Baker Flits With No-Hitter Again|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=A_UhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6aAFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4978,4697692&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Reading Eagle|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=29 July 1980}}</ref> In his final season with the Mariners, Stein batted .268 with 16 runs scored, 53 hits, five doubles, one triple, five home runs, and 27 RBIs in 67 games played. Defensively, he played 34 games at third base, 14 games at second base, and eight games at first base. He also played five games that season as Seattle's designated hitter.

===Texas Rangers===
In December 1980, Stein was signed as a [[free agent]] by the Texas Rangers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers also take Bill Stein|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QMopAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Xe4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=2143,2855349&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=The Spokesman-Review|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=21 December 1980}}</ref> Stein made his Rangers debut on April 14, 1981, against the Cleveland Indians.<ref name="81log">{{cite web|title=Bill Stein 1981 Batting Gamelogs|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=steinbi02&t=b&year=1981|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> In that game, he got one hit in two at-bats.<ref name=81log /> In May, Stein set an American League record by recording seven consecutive pinch hits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stein Sets Pinch-Hit Record|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1981/05/26/sports/stein-sets-pinch-hit-record.html|work=United Press International|publisher=The New York Times Company (subscription required)|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=26 May 1981}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Stein great in a pinch|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=1DotAAAAIBAJ&sjid=b74EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5652,2613902&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=The Rock Hill Herald|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=26 May 1981}}</ref> Through June, Stein had a .441 batting average.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pickard|first=Chuck|title=Let's Hear if for a Little Known Record Holder|journal=Baseball Digest|date=April 1982|volume=41|issue=4|pages=128|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=iDQDAAAAMBAJ&dq=Bill+Stein&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=27 November 2010|page=61|publisher=Lakeside Publishing Co.|language=English|issn=0005-609X}}</ref> On the season, Stein batted .330 with 21 runs scored, 38 hits, six doubles, two home runs, and 22 RBIs in 53 games played. In the field, he played 20 games at first base, seven games at third base, seven games in left field, three games at second base, one game in right field, and one game at shortstop.

On April 16, 1982, in a game against the Milwaukee Brewers, Stein hit a game-winning double in the top of the ninth inning.<ref>{{cite web|last=Aschburner|first=Steve|title=Hitter Stein wins specialists' duel|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yX4hAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RosFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3703,3994522&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=The Milwaukee Journal|publisher=The Milwaukee Journal|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=17 April 1981}}</ref> In June, while playing against his former team, the Seattle Mariners, Stein praised their pitching staff.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stein has the answer: Pitching|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qKASAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZfkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7206,735336&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=United Press International|publisher=Spokane Chronicle|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=17 June 1982}}</ref> In 85 games that year, Stein batted .239, the lowest average of his career since the 1972 season where he played with the St. Louis Cardinals. He also compiled 14 runs scored, 44 hits, eight doubles, one home run, and 16 RBIs. In the field, he played 34 games at second base, 28 games at third base, six games at shortstop, two games at first base, and one game in left field. Stein also was the designated hitter during three games.

In March 1983, Stein praised the Texas Rangers new manager, [[Doug Rader]], for working on the game in a "serious" way.<ref>{{cite web|title=Once a flake: Doug Rader says it's all in the past|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=x8JaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G1kDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3165,2621405&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=The Evening Independent|publisher=The Evening Independent|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=24 March 1983}}</ref> On May 18, in a game against the Cleveland Indians, Stein was brought in as a pinch hitter during the [[extra innings|14{{sup|th}} inning]], and proceeded to get the game winning hit for the Rangers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steins' single sinks Indians in 14th|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ekdPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JwMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6153,6131322&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Toledo Blade|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=19 May 1983}}</ref> With Texas that year, he batted .310 with 21 runs scored, 72 hits, 15 doubles, one triple, two home runs, and 33 RBIs in 78 games played. Stein played the majority of his games at second base, but also played first base and third base. He was used as the Rangers designated hitter in six contests that year. After the season, Stein spoke out against a transaction that the Rangers made, trading [[Jim Sundberg]] to the Milwaukee Brewers, calling him a "mainstay of the organization".<ref>{{cite web|title=Texas Trades Sundberg to Milwaukee Brewers|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DClbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=a08NAAAAIBAJ&pg=6635,4499945&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=The Bonham Daily Favorite|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=9 December 1983}}</ref>

In 1984, the Associated Press stated that Stein was one of the American League's best pinch hitters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Minnesota, Kansas City Even With 17 Games Left|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4GAzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RgYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6707,6700537&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Ocala Star-Banner|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=13 September 1984}}</ref> Early into the season, he injured his [[wrist]], which caused him to miss some playing time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Other 13 -- No Title|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/baltsun/access/1864524902.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=May+04,+1984&author=&pub=The+Sun+(1837-1985)&desc=Other+13+--+No+Title&pqatl=google|work=The Baltimore Sun (subscription required)|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=4 May 1984}}</ref> In mid-June, the Rangers activated him from the disabled list.<ref>{{cite web|title=American League|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cldOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jvkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6072,2902212&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Spokane Chronicle|publisher=Spokane Chronicle|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=14 June 1984}}</ref> On the season, Stein batted .279 with three runs scored, 12 hits, one double and three RBIs in 27 games played. Stein played 11 games at second base, three games at first base, and three games at third base. He also spent four games as the Rangers designated hitter.

Before the 1985 season, it was announced that the Texas Rangers had traded Stein to the Pittsburgh Pirates in exchange for a [[player to be named later]], pending a physical.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers pick up Stein|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CA9RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z8QMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3692,804971&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=United Press International|publisher=The Telegraph-Herald|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=6 January 1985}}</ref> The Pirates later canceled the trade after team doctors discovered a "probable [[Intervertebral disc|disc]] problem" in his back.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bucks deal for Stein canceled|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BwgOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=P24DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4936,2297125&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=10 January 1985}}</ref> Rumors then circulated that it was possible that Steins' career would be ended by the injury.<ref>{{cite web|title=Names and Games|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-XIdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HWMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7135,4320230&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=The Pittsburgh Press|publisher=The Pittsburgh Press|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=10 January 1985}}</ref> However, Stein did play 44 games with the Rangers that season, batting .253 with five runs scored, 20 hits, three doubles, one triple, one home run, and 12 RBIs. He played 11 games at third base, eight games at first base, three games at second base, and three games in right field. Stein was the team's designated hitter in six games that year. In his final season in the majors, he earned a salary of $250,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|250000|1985}}}} inflation adjusted). At the end of the season, Texas announced that it would not re-sign Stein.<ref name="texas">{{cite web|last=Kurkjian|first=Tim|title=Stein not offered contract from Rangers|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3CDB5DD3C07D0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|work=The Dallas Morning News (subscription required)|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=24 October 1985}}</ref> Through an agent, Stein commented that if he could not play for Texas in the upcoming season, he would retire.<ref name=texas />

==Coaching career==
In 1987, Stein [[coach (baseball)|coached]] the [[Rockledge High School]] baseball team, leading them a district title with a 17<U+2013>11 [[win<U+2013>loss record|record]].<ref name="88coach">{{cite web|last=Zizzo|first=Mike|title=Stein named to manage in the Mets system|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/orlandosentinel/access/89145519.html?dids=89145519:89145519&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+02,+1988&author=Mike+Zizzo+of+The+Sentinel+Staff&pub=Orlando+Sentinel&desc=ROCKLEDGE'S+STEIN+NAMED+TO+MANAGE+IN+METS+CHAIN&pqatl=google|work=Orlando Sentinel (subscription required)|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=2 June 1988}}</ref> Stein was hired as the manager of the [[Minor league baseball#Class A-Short Season|Class-A Short Season]] [[Little Falls Mets]] of the [[New York<U+2013>Penn League]] in 1988.<ref name=88coach /> Little Falls were minor league affiliates of the [[New York Mets]].<ref name=88coach /> In his first professional season as a manager, Stein led Little Falls to a 39<U+2013>36 record.<ref>{{cite web|title=1988 Little Falls Mets|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=23010|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> Stein commented that when he became a manager it was difficult to learn pitching after all the years of being a [[position player]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Zizzo|first=Mike|title=Former major leaguer Stein finally has to adjust to Class A ball|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/orlandosentinel/access/89168431.html?dids=89168431:89168431&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+07,+1988&author=Mike+Zizzo+of+the+Sentinel+Staff&pub=Orlando+Sentinel&desc=FORMER+MAJOR-LEAGUER+STEIN+FINALLY+HAS+TO+ADJUST+TO+CLASS+A+BALL&pqatl=google|work=Orlando Sentinel (subscription required)|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=7 June 1988}}</ref> In 1989, the New York Mets fired [[Butch Hobson]], the manager of the [[minor league baseball#Class A|Class-A]] [[Columbia Mets]], and promoted Stein to that position.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bill Stein to manage Colombia Mets|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DywtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ibsEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5322,1809344&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=The Rock Hill Herald|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=12 January 1989}}</ref> At the helm of Colombia that year, Stein led them to a 73<U+2013>67 record.<ref>{{cite web|title=1989 Columbia Mets|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=15587|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> He also served as a [[player-coach]] with the [[Orlando Juice]] of the [[Senior Professional Baseball Association]] in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|last=Zizzo|first=Mike|title=Bill Stein returns to playing utility infielder, signs with Orlando Rays|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/orlandosentinel/access/89900872.html?dids=89900872:89900872&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+05,+1989&author=Mike+Zizzo+of+The+Sentinel+Staff&pub=Orlando+Sentinel&desc=BILL+STEIN+RETURNS+TO+PLAYING+UTILITY+INFIELDER+SIGNS+WITH+ORLANDO+JUICE&pqatl=google|work=Orlando Sentinel (subscription required)|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=5 October 1989}}</ref> 

Stein continued to manage the Columbia Mets in 1990, leading them to a 83<U+2013>60 record.<ref>{{cite web|title=1990 Columbia Mets|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=15588|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> The Mets had the best record in the [[South Atlantic League]] that season.<ref>{{cite web|title=1990 South Atlantic League|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/league.cgi?id=13903|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> In 1991, Stein was hired to be the manager of the [[Bend Bucks]] of the [[Northwest League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=M's could count on Bend skipper|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qaIpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1_ADAAAAIBAJ&pg=6522,2536428&dq=bill+stein&hl=en|work=The Spokesman-Review|publisher=The Spokesman-Review|accessdate=27 November 2010|date=23 July 1990}}</ref> The non-affiliated Bucks had a record of 30<U+2013>46 with Stein as the manager.<ref>{{cite web|title=1991 Bend Bucks|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=12028|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=28 November 2010}}</ref> He was hired to be the manager of the [[Clinton Giants]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jones sparks Reds coming off the bench|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CR&z=CRGB&p_theme=cr&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAFE66D2AB0F54F&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|work=The Gazette (subscription required)|accessdate=28 November 2010|date=19 April 1992}}</ref> Clinton was the Class-A affiliate of the [[San Francisco Giants]] at the time.<ref name="clinton">{{cite web|title=1992 Clinton Giants|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=15401|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=28 November 2010}}</ref> Stein led Clinton to a 59<U+2013>79 record that year.<ref name=clinton /> After considering taking a year off of baseball in 1994, Stein eventually accepted the managerial position with the [[independent league baseball|independent league]] [[Tyler WildCatters]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Small team, big dream It might be the minors...but it's all major fun|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF8F96C22469F4&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|work=Fort Worth Star-Telegram (subscription required)|accessdate=28 November 2010|date=21 August 1994}}</ref>

